<h3  style="color: black; font-style: calibri-body;">  What we do </h3>

<hr>

<p  style="color: white;"> This is a website to help any new PC builders find their way in building their own personal rig.<br>
It may seem daunting at first, but it is not very difficult. Think of it as LEGO.<br>
It is proven that it is 40% cheaper to build a PC vs. buying it. <a href="https://www.pcreview.co.uk/articles/how-much-money-can-you-save-by-building-your-own-pc.101/">Source</a>

<h2 style="color: black;"> <u> Step 1: Gather Parts </u> </h2>

<p style="color: white;"> Planning is important. "Fail to prepare, prepare to fail".  Thats why I would recommend <a href="https://pcpartpicker.com/list/">PCPartPicker</a> for all your planning needs.<br>
You should create a PCPartPicker list and ask some people who know more or consult a guide like this. That would set you on good track to complete your build. </p>

<h3 style="color: white;"> Recommendations </h3>

<p style="color: white;"> In 2018, the are basic recommendations to make your rig run as smoothly as possible. These include: </p>

<h4> Having an SSD </h4>

<center><img src="SSD2.jpg" alt="SSD" height=300 width=490></center>

<p style="color: white;"> If your build is going to cost upwards of £500, it should have an SSD. Its main purpose is to be used as a boot drive (the drive you put the operating system on)<br>
and also any files that your system may need quickly (like drivers and other system files), but also programs you use regularly (like Microsoft Word etc.). This means that they will load faster. </p>

<h4> Getting a decent power supply </h4>


<center><img src="80plus.jpg" alt="80+" height=300 width=600></center>


<p style="color: white;"> The last thing you want in your build is a fire that ruins all your parts. That is why you should invest in atleast an 80+ certified power supply<br>
from a reputable manufacturer. This will give you peace of mind that your rig won't blow up in your face. Manufactures I would recommend:<br>

<ul style="color: white";>
   <li>Corsair</li>
   <li>BeQuiet!</li>
   <li>EVGA</li>
   <li>Cooler Master</li>
   <li>Enermax</li>
   <li>NZXT</li>
   <li>Thermaltake</li>
   <li>XFX</li>
</ul>



<p style="color: white";> Here's a handy <a href="https://linustechtips.com/main/topic/631048-psu-tier-list-updated/">PSU tier list</a> <br>
and good video on how much wattage you need
</p>


<center>
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/lXku-gsdyok" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</center>

<h2> Plan out your parts </h2>

<p style="color: white;"> Next, once you have a vague idea of what you want, plan out your build with PCPartPicker. Here are some build guidlines that I would have in 2018. </p>

<h3> The Budget Build </h3>

<p style="color: white;"> This is the build for people who are on a very tight budget but still want to game. It is a good all-rounder.<br>
The added silent video card helps with noise. This build is good for 720p ultra settings or 1080p medium settings. </p>

