<h2> <u> Step 2: Get Ready </u> </h2>

<hr>

<p style="color: white;"> For newer builders, it may be advisable to add some protection from electrostatic shocks.<br>
Things like anti-static wristbands can be the difference between a clean build and one that ends in disaster and lots of money needing to be spent because of the fact that manufacturers don't<br>
cover damage from electro-static shocks. </p>

<p style="color: white;"> A method I would recommend is using an anti-static wriststrap <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/mercury-710-131-Antistatic-Wrist-Band-blue/dp/B000L98002">like this one.</a> <br>
Otherwise, you should always not have any big jumpers on and don't pet animals. Always touch the case before you touch any components.</p>

<h2> <u> Step 3: Start Building </u> </h2>

<p style="color: white;"> The first step is to make a testbench. This will mean that you can test all the parts before <br>
  putting them inside the case. </p>


<center><img src="MotherBoardTestBench.jpg" alt="testbench" height="400px" width="600"></center>

<p> Then,
